# 📚 Readly Bookstore – Architecture Options

This document outlines different architecture approaches for building the **Readly Bookstore** application.

---

## 🧩 Overview

| Option           | Frontend | Backend                     | Database            | Description                          |
| ---------------- | -------- | --------------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| **A (Current)**  | Next.js  | Supabase (BaaS)             | Supabase PostgreSQL | Fully managed backend using Supabase |
| **B**            | Next.js  | Spring Boot REST API        | MySQL / PostgreSQL  | Custom backend with Java             |
| **C (Overkill)** | Next.js  | Spring Boot + Supabase Auth | PostgreSQL          | Hybrid architecture with both        |

---

## ✅ Option A – Next.js + Supabase (Current)

### 📌 Stack

* Frontend: Next.js (App Router)
* Backend: Supabase (Auth, APIs, Storage)
* Database: PostgreSQL (managed by Supabase)

### 👍 Advantages

* Fast development
* No backend setup required
* Built-in authentication & database
* Ideal for MVP and portfolio projects

### 👎 Limitations

* Less backend control
* Business logic tied to Supabase
* Not ideal for complex enterprise systems

---

## ⚙️ Option B – Next.js + Spring Boot

### 📌 Stack

* Frontend: Next.js
* Backend: Spring Boot (REST APIs)
* Database: MySQL / PostgreSQL

### 👍 Advantages

* Full control over backend logic
* Strong architecture (Controller → Service → Repository)
* Industry-standard for enterprise apps
* Better for interviews (Java + Spring Boot)

### 👎 Limitations

* More development time
* Requires backend deployment & management
* Need to implement authentication manually (JWT, OAuth)

---

## 🚀 Option C – Hybrid (Overkill)

### 📌 Stack

* Frontend: Next.js
* Backend: Spring Boot (Business Logic)
* Auth: Supabase Authentication
* Database: PostgreSQL

### 👍 Advantages

* Combines best of both worlds
* Supabase handles authentication
* Spring Boot handles business logic

### 👎 Limitations

* Increased complexity
* Harder to maintain
* Not recommended for beginners or small projects

---

## 🎯 Recommendation

For this project:

👉 **Use Option A (Next.js + Supabase)**

* Best for speed, simplicity, and portfolio projects

👉 **Upgrade to Option B if:**

* You want strong backend skills
* You are preparing for Java/Spring Boot interviews

---

## 🧠 Interview Tip

You can say:

> “I initially built the project using Supabase for rapid development.
> Then I explored a scalable architecture using Spring Boot REST APIs
> to demonstrate backend expertise and separation of concerns.”

---

## 📌 Final Verdict

| Use Case                | Best Option |
| ----------------------- | ----------- |
| Portfolio / MVP         | ✅ Option A  |
| Backend Learning        | ✅ Option B  |
| Enterprise-level system | ⚙️ Option B |
| Experimentation         | 🚫 Option C |

